Exploratory Text Analysis before cleaning the text¶

rev = pd.read_csv("yelp.csv")

1. Word Count : One of the most basic features we can extract is the number of words in reviews. The basic intuition behind this is that generally, the negative sentiments contain a lesser amount of words than the positive ones. Lets see how that intution goes about.¶

In [61]:
#Number of words
rev['word_count'] = rev['text'].apply(lambda x: len(str(x).split(" ")))
rev[['word_count','text']].head()

3. Average word length is an important for helping in improving our model.¶

In [65]:
def avg_word(sentence):
  words = sentence.split()
  return (sum(len(word) for word in words)/len(words))

rev['avg_word'] = rev['text'].apply(lambda x: avg_word(x))
rev[['text','avg_word']].head()

aw = []
for i in range(1,6):
    cl = rev[rev['stars']== i]['avg_word'].mean()
    print("The average character count for reviews with ",i," star is",rev[rev['stars']== i]['avg_word'].mean())
    aw.append(cl)
str1 = ['1','2','3','4','5']
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
plt.scatter(str1,aw)
plt.xlabel('Star')
plt.ylabel('Average word length')
plt.title('Average Word length of reviews with different star ratings')

4. Analyzing the number of stop words. I will be using the nltk package english package to analyze the stop words.¶

In [66]:
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
stop = stopwords.words('english')

rev['stop_words'] = rev['text'].apply(lambda x: len([x for x in x.split() if x in stop]))
In [67]:

5. Number of numeric characters used. Like calculating the number of words, we can calculate the number of numeric characters which are present in the reviews.¶

In [68]:
rev['numerics'] = rev['text'].apply(lambda x: len([x for x in x.split() if x.isdigit()]))
rev[['text','numerics']].head()
nm=[]
for i in range(1,6):
    nm1 = rev[rev['stars']== i]['numerics'].sum()
    print("The count of numeric characters for reviews with ",i," star is",rev[rev['stars']== i]['numerics'].sum())
    nm.append(nm1)
str1 = ['1','2','3','4','5']
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
sns.barplot(str1,nm,palette='pastel')
plt.xlabel('Star')
plt.ylabel('Count of numeric characters')
plt.title('Count of numeric characters used in reviews with different star ratings')
   

The count of numeric characters for reviews with  1  star is 664
The count of numeric characters for reviews with  2  star is 685
The count of numeric characters for reviews with  3  star is 929
The count of numeric characters for reviews with  4  star is 1688
The count of numeric characters for reviews with  5  star is 1311
Out[68]:
Text(0.5,1,'Count of numeric characters used in reviews with different star ratings')

This analysis gives an interesting view of how people use many numerics in relatively positive comments than negative comments, the usage of numerics in happy reviews are twice than that of bad comments.¶

Basic data cleaning for data visualization¶

from nltk.corpus import stopwords
stop = stopwords.words('english')
stop.extend(['place','food','order','got','really','one','like','go','would','back','also','get','always','even','us'])
from nltk.stem import PorterStemmer
st = PorterStemmer()
def clean(a):
    a = a.apply(lambda x: " ".join(x.lower() for x in x.split())) #Converting to lower case
    a = a.str.replace("[^a-zA-Z#]", " ") #Removing punctuation 
    a = a.apply(lambda x: " ".join(x for x in x.split() if x not in stop)) #Removing stop words
    return(a)

Data Preprocessing - Text Cleaning for building the model¶

People would generally be interested in the main aspect of the project which to identify if a review is either positive or negative and neutral scenarios are extremely rare and especially when you are a customer or someone at Yelp you would need you algorithm to check if a new incoming review is positive or negative. So, as mentioned in the proposal, I am looking to build a model if a review is either positive or negative, so considering only the data which contains rating 1 or 5 makes sense.¶

X = reviews['text']
y = reviews['stars']
In [80]:
import string
def clean_text(text):
    clean = [char for char in text if char not in string.punctuation] #Remove punctuations
    clean = ''.join(clean) #Changing to uniform lower case characters
    return [word for word in clean.split() if word.lower() not in stopwords.words('english')] #Removing the stop words
Our Machine learning algorithms work when the text is vectorized and in numerics than the actual text which can be done using the Scikit learn, which converts text into matrix of tokens¶
In [81]:
#Vectorization
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
bow_transformer = CountVectorizer(analyzer=clean_text).fit(X)
In [82]:

di = [Naive_bayes,Logistic_reg,Random_for,Decision_tre]

for i,j in zip(di,dj):
    print("The scores for the model",j,"are as below")
    print('\n')
    bn = i.fit(X_train,  y_train)
    preds_lr = bn.predict(X_test)
    print("Confusion Matrix")
    print(confusion_matrix(y_test, preds_lr))
    print('\n')
    print("Classification Report")
    print(classification_report(y_test, preds_lr))
    print("The accuracy score for the model",j,"is",accuracy_score(y_test, preds_lr))
    print('****************************************************************************')
